Most. Ι. i. 55, Qui scis, i. e. ‘ how do you know ?'

The use of Qui for quomodo or qua ratione in direct questions is familiar to us from Horace, who employs it repeatedly in that sense,* as do Cicero and Persius. When the word is used in this manner many grammarians call it an adverb, but it is in reality an old form of the ablative of quis, and it stands for the ablative of the relative in all genders.
